{
  "text": " One pattern in about a third of my chronic inflammation cases that keeps coming up. Client has tried every protocol, antihistamines, gut work, nervous system regulation, elimination diet. Some things help for a week. Then the symptoms come back, usually in the same places, usually at the same times. Nobody can map it because the protocol was not designed to map it. Here's what I asked them to track. Which rooms? Which buildings? Which days of the week? Within two weeks, the map is obvious. Find it work, sick at home, or find in the new office, sick in the car, or find on vacation. Back to square one in the bedroom. This is almost always a mycotoxin load pattern, not mold generally. A specific mycotoxin from a specific building material producing a specific symptom cluster. Ocratoxin from water damage drywall looks different from aflatoxin from contaminated food. Gleeotoxin from indoor growth looks different from tricotocines, eight mycotoxins, eight symptom profiles. Broad spectrum treatment keeps missing because the target is specific. A light formula is published as mycotoxin-specific clinical guides. Each one covers the source mold, the organ at targets, the differentiating symptom profile. Full pattern breakdown at tr.e.e. slash owq7fm. Type it.",
